contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

11:10.303 --> 11:11.771
All right, who is the weirdo

11:11.871 --> 11:14.204
who voted
"not-guilty-a-mundo," huh?

11:14.307 --> 11:15.468
Aaayyhg

11:15.575 --> 11:17.543
HOWARD:
There will be...

11:17.644 --> 11:20.909
there will be
no name-calling on myjury.

11:21.014 --> 11:22.777
Now, look...

11:22.882 --> 11:25.852
I mean, it appears to me that
you're not too worried about

11:25.952 --> 11:28.819
whether you send an innocent man
to jail or not, right?

11:28.922 --> 11:32.085
You all want to get home to your
middle-class homes so quickly.

11:32.192 --> 11:34.956
All right, but at least
let's go over the facts.

11:35.061 --> 11:37.928
We all know the facts: the kid's
guilty; that's the facts.

11:38.031 --> 11:39.191
(low, indistinct chatter)

11:39.299 --> 11:40.493
Guilty is a verdict.

11:40.600 --> 11:42.227
Guilty's is not a fact.

11:42.335 --> 11:44.599
Huh? Huh?
(chuckles)

11:44.704 --> 11:49.540
Look, I happen to think
that Mr. Davis is not guilty.

11:49.642 --> 11:51.201
Mr. Davis?

11:51.311 --> 11:54.246
Oh-ho, now I know
why you're fighting for him.

11:54.347 --> 11:56.315
He's another one
of those bikers.

11:56.416 --> 11:58.714
And none of you are any good.

11:58.818 --> 12:01.151
Fonzie...

12:01.254 --> 12:02.653
HOWARD:
Sit down, Burch.

12:04.023 --> 12:06.424
Now, look, if there's
one member of this jury

12:06.526 --> 12:08.790
who happens to think
that the defendant is innocent,

12:08.895 --> 12:11.227
well, then he's got
a right to be heard.

12:11.331 --> 12:13.424
Thanks a lot, Mr. C.

12:13.533 --> 12:16.866
What's the big deal, Fonzie?
I mean... (speaks quietly)

12:16.970 --> 12:19.837
Hey, look, it is just like
the defense lawyer said--

12:19.939 --> 12:22.431
it is "circumventive" evidence.

12:22.542 --> 12:24.806
- That's circumstantial evidence.
- Or whatever.

12:24.911 --> 12:27.175
I got a gut feeling, Mr. C.

12:27.280 --> 12:29.180
But it's not the same thing.

12:29.282 --> 12:31.182
A gut feeling is a gut feeling.

12:31.284 --> 12:33.878
It's the same one I had
when I was just thinking

12:33.987 --> 12:35.454
about dating
the Hooper triplets.

12:35.555 --> 12:39.719
I had two yesses and a maybe,
but I stuck it out.

12:39.826 --> 12:41.384
- What happened?
- Later.

12:41.494 --> 12:42.518
Oh.

12:42.629 --> 12:44.790
Can we get on with this?

12:44.897 --> 12:46.331
MALE JUROR:
Yeah.

12:46.432 --> 12:48.526
All right.
You want jurisprudence?

12:48.635 --> 12:49.829
I'll give you jurisprudence.

12:49.936 --> 12:51.904
With a little mixture
of evidence, all right?

12:52.005 --> 12:53.871
Now, look, the eyewitness

12:53.973 --> 12:55.737
couldn't even give us
the license plate number.

12:55.842 --> 12:57.435
She couldn't even tell you

12:57.543 --> 12:59.478
what kind of bike
the man was riding.

12:59.579 --> 13:02.105
She identified the man
by the helmet-- right here.

13:03.349 --> 13:04.942
Exhibit A, all right?

13:05.051 --> 13:06.450
Now, look, I want to try
a little experiment,

13:06.552 --> 13:08.179
I'm going to put on
Exhibit A, all right?

13:08.288 --> 13:11.621
Now, when the guy
was driving away,

13:11.724 --> 13:12.953
he was in this position.

13:13.059 --> 13:14.527
Tell me...

13:14.627 --> 13:16.095
what color are my eyes?

13:16.195 --> 13:18.391
But Fonzie,
we can't see your face.

13:18.498 --> 13:20.022
Correct-a-mundo.

13:20.133 --> 13:23.592
The eyewitness couldn't see
the man's face, either.

13:23.703 --> 13:25.068
She identified the helmet.

13:25.171 --> 13:26.866
I'm telling you,
Milwaukee is filled

13:26.973 --> 13:28.202
with this kind of helmet.

13:28.308 --> 13:30.674
Oh, yeah, but don't forget...

13:30.777 --> 13:32.540
that guy was caught
two blocks away

13:32.645 --> 13:34.511
going through
Mrs. Leary's purse.

13:34.614 --> 13:36.605
And don't forget,
that guy said that he was

13:36.716 --> 13:39.481
going through the purse
looking for identification.

13:39.585 --> 13:41.611
They will say anything.

13:41.721 --> 13:43.951
Now wait a minute, Burch.

13:44.057 --> 13:47.424
The judge happened to say
"reasonable doubt,"

13:47.527 --> 13:48.756
and it's quite obvious here

13:48.861 --> 13:50.591
that Fonzie has
a reasonable doubt.

13:50.697 --> 13:51.891
Correct-a-mundo.

13:51.998 --> 13:53.864
Oh, "mundo" again.

13:53.966 --> 13:56.060
Are you sure
you're an American, huh?

13:58.705 --> 14:02.300
Right down to my red,
white and blue socks.

14:10.283 --> 14:11.910
BURCH:
Look...

14:12.018 --> 14:13.486
I say, let's stop fooling around

14:13.586 --> 14:14.986
and string this guy...

14:16.989 --> 14:20.255
No, I mean, let's get
this thing over with

14:20.360 --> 14:21.918
so we can all go home, right?

14:22.028 --> 14:23.291
- Yeah. -Yeah, let's go.
- Let's get out of here.

14:23.396 --> 14:25.296
All right, all right.

14:25.398 --> 14:27.161
It looks like you don't care--
that's fine.

14:27.266 --> 14:28.495
Let's take another vote.

14:28.601 --> 14:29.625
Good.

14:29.736 --> 14:31.363
And if you all think

14:31.471 --> 14:34.201
that Mr. Davis is guilty,
then, uh...

14:34.307 --> 14:36.400
I'll vote the same way.

14:36.509 --> 14:38.307
All right,
let's have a show of hands.

14:38.411 --> 14:40.675
All those for guilty,
put 'em up.

14:41.848 --> 14:44.578
What about you, Mr. Foreman?

14:44.684 --> 14:46.584
- I vote not guilty.
- What?

14:46.686 --> 14:48.119
Hey, I convinced you,
huh, Mr. C.?

14:48.221 --> 14:49.711
No, you didn't convince me,
Fonzie.

14:49.822 --> 14:51.916
I still think he's guilty.

14:52.024 --> 14:53.925
But I'm not going
to put a man in jail

14:54.026 --> 14:55.688
just because I'm
in a hurry to get home.

14:55.795 --> 14:58.287
Hey, attaboy, Mr. C.

14:58.398 --> 15:00.730
What color are your socks?

15:06.339 --> 15:08.899
Hey, I-I'm doing
pretty good, huh?

15:09.008 --> 15:11.067
- Wasn't I good today?
- Oh...

15:11.177 --> 15:14.408
You were so good
we gotta go back tomorrow.

15:14.514 --> 15:16.209
Try and figure out
what this thing is...

15:16.315 --> 15:18.011
- Hey, hey, hey, hey, hey...
- Oh.

15:18.117 --> 15:19.778
Can't I even talk to my wife?

15:19.886 --> 15:22.650
Hey, the judge says we don't
discuss this case with nobody.

15:22.755 --> 15:25.918
Oh, good,
you got a juicy trial.

15:26.025 --> 15:27.755
Yes, we've got
a juicy trial, Marion,

15:27.860 --> 15:29.191
and Fonzie here is the one...

15:29.295 --> 15:30.456
Hey, hey, hey, hey, hey, hey.

15:30.563 --> 15:33.123
Mm-mm.

15:33.232 --> 15:34.791
I tell you something, Mrs. C,

15:34.901 --> 15:37.062
there is something about
this case that is bugging me.

15:37.170 --> 15:39.331
I'm going down to the "liberry"
to study up on jurisprudence,

15:39.439 --> 15:40.633
-you know.
- Uh-uh. -Uh-uh.

15:40.740 --> 15:43.766
Hey, hey. The rule
in the "liberry" is silence.

15:43.876 --> 15:45.867
Hey.

15:46.913 --> 15:49.746
Well, how did
the paint sale go, huh?

15:49.849 --> 15:52.215
Oh, the paint sale!
It was such fun.

15:52.318 --> 15:54.309
Fun?!

15:55.188 --> 15:56.382
Oh, it started slow,

15:56.489 --> 15:57.820
and then I just did

15:57.924 --> 15:59.653
the same thing
that the drugstore does.

15:59.759 --> 16:01.625
I had a one-cent sale.

16:04.931 --> 16:07.957
You had a one-cent sale?

16:08.067 --> 16:10.229
Well, I wasn't sure the idea
would work at first,

16:10.336 --> 16:12.566
but I just said,
"Marion, why not?"

16:12.672 --> 16:14.902
And, Howard, you know what?

16:15.007 --> 16:18.466
I sold out
your entire inventory.

16:20.847 --> 16:26.149
You mean you sold half of
my inventory for a penny a can?

16:26.252 --> 16:27.151
(chortling)

16:27.253 --> 16:29.085
I can't believe this!

16:29.188 --> 16:31.885
You drove me to bankruptcy
while I'm locked up

16:31.991 --> 16:34.358
-in a courtroom trying to...
- Ah, ah, ah.

16:34.460 --> 16:35.689
(sighs)

16:35.795 --> 16:38.093
I'm broke, I can't talk--

16:38.197 --> 16:40.359
what else can happen to me?

16:40.466 --> 16:43.527
All right,
the Three Caballeros are ready!

16:43.636 --> 16:46.230
That's what else could happen
to me!

16:46.339 --> 16:48.239
JOANIE: Okay, boys, make it
good! We have an audience!

16:48.341 --> 16:49.240
(Howard groans)

16:49.342 --> 16:50.900
Ladies and gentlemen,

16:51.010 --> 16:52.910
from Alpha Tau Omega,

16:53.012 --> 16:54.912
the Three Caballeros!

16:55.014 --> 16:57.449
(playing jaunty Latin intro)

16:57.550 --> 16:59.450
-(shouting, yipping)
- Olé! Olé!

16:59.552 --> 17:01.452
Pancho!

17:01.554 --> 17:03.454
Fernando!

17:03.556 --> 17:04.614
Uh...

17:04.723 --> 17:07.021
- Pepe! -Pepe, Potsie!
- Oh, yeah! Right, right!

17:07.126 --> 17:09.151
Let's go. guys!

17:10.530 --> 17:11.929
♪ We're three caballeros ♪

17:12.031 --> 17:13.795
♪ Three gay caballeros ♪

17:13.900 --> 17:17.097
♪ They say we are birds
of a feather ♪

17:17.203 --> 17:20.400
- RALPH: Olé!
- POTSIE: iArriba!

17:20.506 --> 17:22.406
♪ We're happy amigos ♪

17:22.508 --> 17:24.407
♪ No matter where he goes ♪

17:24.510 --> 17:25.944
♪ The one, two and three goes ♪

17:26.045 --> 17:28.343
♪ We're always together ♪

17:28.446 --> 17:30.939
<i>Howie. Arriba.</i>

17:31.050 --> 17:32.415
- Olé!
- Olé.

17:32.518 --> 17:34.248
♪ We're three happy chappies ♪

17:34.353 --> 17:35.787
♪ With snappy serapes ♪

17:35.888 --> 17:39.449
♪ You'll find us
beneath our sombreros ♪

17:39.559 --> 17:42.460
-(tri I I I ng)
- Olé. Arriba.

17:42.562 --> 17:44.462
♪ We're brave and we'll say so ♪

17:44.564 --> 17:46.259
♪ We're bright as a peso ♪

17:46.365 --> 17:47.924
- ♪ Who says so? ♪
- ♪ We say so! ♪

17:48.034 --> 17:51.265
♪ The three caballeros ♪

17:51.370 --> 17:53.066
♪ iPor favor! ♪

17:54.273 --> 17:55.502
Not bad, huh?

17:56.776 --> 18:00.769
You know, the parrot
didn't sound half bad.

18:04.016 --> 18:05.575
BURCH:
Aw, come on,

18:05.685 --> 18:06.777
talk, talk, talk.

18:06.886 --> 18:09.252
Another "not guilty-a-mundo."

18:09.355 --> 18:12.416
Look, I don't care
about Mr. Fonzareeny.

18:12.525 --> 18:13.856
Fonzarelli.

18:13.960 --> 18:15.860
Whatever-arelli.

18:15.962 --> 18:17.827
The guy is guilty.

18:17.930 --> 18:21.059
No, he is not.

18:22.868 --> 18:25.895
Fonzie, I've given you
every opportunity

18:26.005 --> 18:27.632
to express your views.

18:27.740 --> 18:31.040
Now, unfortunately,
your gut feelings of innocence

18:31.143 --> 18:33.476
do not negate the facts
in this case.

18:33.579 --> 18:35.206
What's "negate" mean?

18:35.314 --> 18:37.180
"Negate" means "deny."

18:37.283 --> 18:39.376
Hey, good word, good word.

18:39.485 --> 18:40.714
Quiet.

18:40.820 --> 18:42.344
Another good word.

18:44.123 --> 18:46.615
Now, look, unless you come up
with some hard facts

18:46.726 --> 18:49.286
to prove that the defendant
is innocent,

18:49.395 --> 18:51.420
then I'm gonna have
to take another vote.

18:52.465 --> 18:54.365
(Howard sighs)

18:54.467 --> 18:55.957
All right.

18:56.068 --> 18:57.627
All right,
let's take another vote.

18:57.737 --> 19:00.228
All those who say
that the defendant is guilty,

19:00.339 --> 19:03.707
raise your hands.

19:03.809 --> 19:05.641
All right, let the record show

19:05.745 --> 19:07.269
that we find that
the defendant is guilty...

19:07.380 --> 19:09.348
Oh, oh, oh, oh!
Hold it, hold it, hold it!

19:09.448 --> 19:11.144
Oh, here we go again.

19:11.250 --> 19:13.344
No, wait a minute, please--
just wait a minute.

19:13.452 --> 19:16.422
Look, it says right here
in the transcript,

19:16.522 --> 19:20.755
Jason Davis was riding
a Graham Mark Two motorcycle

19:20.860 --> 19:22.225
when he was picked up.

19:22.328 --> 19:24.353
- We know that, Fonzie.
- That's right.

19:24.463 --> 19:26.159
You know that,
but do you know, Mr. C.,

19:26.265 --> 19:29.098
that the Graham Mark Two
is a very rare bike,

19:29.201 --> 19:31.500
and it's only made in England?

19:31.604 --> 19:33.163
That's another thing wrong
with him.

19:33.272 --> 19:35.366
He don't even buy American.

19:35.474 --> 19:36.498
Whoa.

19:36.609 --> 19:38.372
Madam, would you
come here, please, huh?

19:38.477 --> 19:39.672
Just step right over here,
help me out.

19:39.779 --> 19:40.803
That's right.

19:40.913 --> 19:43.109
And hold on to Exhibit B,
the handbag.

19:43.215 --> 19:44.911
Okay, look.

19:45.017 --> 19:47.782
Mrs. Leary is standing
in the parking lot,

19:47.887 --> 19:49.650
holding her little handbag,
right?

19:49.755 --> 19:53.453
Okay, now Jason supposedly
whips by and grabs the--

19:53.559 --> 19:54.788
You're supposed to let go
of the purse, ma'am.

19:54.894 --> 19:55.986
Oh.

19:56.095 --> 19:56.994
Thanks so much.

19:57.096 --> 19:58.188
Whips by, grabs the bag

19:58.297 --> 20:00.027
and holds it up, right?

20:00.132 --> 20:01.600
So?

20:02.635 --> 20:04.865
Come here.

20:04.970 --> 20:08.463
I hate it when people say,
(mocking tone): "So?"

20:12.078 --> 20:13.238
All right...

20:13.345 --> 20:15.007
Now, dig it; now, dig it--

20:15.114 --> 20:16.582
this is the important part.

20:16.682 --> 20:19.845
The criminal was supposed
to have had the handbag

20:19.952 --> 20:22.319
in his left hand.

20:22.421 --> 20:23.616
Well, naturally.

20:23.723 --> 20:25.987
He had to accelerate the bike
with his right hand.

20:26.092 --> 20:28.720
And there's the rub,
ladies and gentlemen.

20:28.828 --> 20:32.389
The Graham Mark Two,
made in England,

20:32.498 --> 20:36.799
has the accelerator
on the left-hand handlebar.

20:36.902 --> 20:38.666
Now, how can Jason Davis

20:38.771 --> 20:41.866
grab the bag, hold it up
in-in his left hand

20:41.974 --> 20:44.068
and accelerate
with the same hand?

20:44.176 --> 20:46.167
With two left hands? He can't.

20:46.278 --> 20:48.178
I rest my case.

20:48.280 --> 20:49.976
Thank you very much.

20:55.054 --> 20:57.147
Let me see this.

20:57.256 --> 20:59.486
That's what's been bugging me
the whole time, Mr. C.

20:59.592 --> 21:01.082
You're right, Fonzie.

21:01.193 --> 21:03.753
It says here that he held up
the purse in his left hand.

21:03.863 --> 21:05.888
Right.
Now, due to the-the evidence

21:05.998 --> 21:08.296
that I've exposed here
to you ladies and gentlemen,

21:08.400 --> 21:10.835
it is impossible
for you to find

21:10.936 --> 21:14.304
Jason Davis guilty.

21:14.406 --> 21:16.170
HOWARD:
Well,

21:16.275 --> 21:17.606
in light
of this new information,

21:17.710 --> 21:19.143
I think we should take
another vote.

21:19.245 --> 21:20.678
- FONZIE: Yeah.
- Hold it. Th-There's still

21:20.780 --> 21:22.179
a little something wrong here.

21:22.281 --> 21:23.578
Only for you.

21:23.682 --> 21:26.777
Mr. Davis can't change
his color. Sorry.

21:26.886 --> 21:28.786
HOWARD:
All right.

21:28.888 --> 21:32.324
All those who vote that
the defendant is not guilty,

21:32.424 --> 21:35.326
raise your hands.

21:35.427 --> 21:36.986
We'll let the record show

21:37.096 --> 21:39.724
that the defendant
is not guilty...

21:39.832 --> 21:42.824
-a-mundo.
- Heyyy.

21:47.039 --> 21:49.838
Do I know my jurisprudence
or do I know my jurisprudence?

21:49.942 --> 21:50.841
Was I not great?

21:50.943 --> 21:52.172
Well, you got him acquitted.

21:52.278 --> 21:54.212
- You did fine, Fonzie.
- Yeah.

21:54.313 --> 21:56.543
I had a great time, but I'm out.

21:56.649 --> 21:59.209
Say, listen,
weren't you on the jury?

21:59.318 --> 22:01.150
Hey, I really want to thank you.

22:01.253 --> 22:04.246
I really want to thank you.

22:05.791 --> 22:07.782
Mm!

22:10.196 --> 22:11.754
Hey, I want
to thank you guys also.

22:11.864 --> 22:14.560
You know, I didn't think
I had a chance in there.

22:14.667 --> 22:17.158
Well, our court system seems
to work a lot better

22:17.269 --> 22:20.501
when you look upon jury duty
as a privilege and not a chore.

22:20.606 --> 22:23.007
- Hey, no objection there, Mr. C.
- Mm.

22:23.108 --> 22:25.270
Oh, and speaking of chores,
I think I better get back

22:25.377 --> 22:27.607
to the store.
I got to get Marion out of there

22:27.713 --> 22:30.512
before I have to have
a going-out-of-business sale.

22:30.616 --> 22:32.050
- I'll see you.
- See you later. -Take it easy.

22:32.151 --> 22:33.983
- Say, you're a biker,
aren't you? -Yeah, that's right.

22:34.086 --> 22:34.985
Want to make
something of it?

22:35.087 --> 22:36.248
- No.
- Just kidding.

22:36.355 --> 22:38.585
Let me ask you a question.

22:38.691 --> 22:41.057
That beautiful bike
you got there, you ever race it?

22:41.160 --> 22:42.992
Oh, yeah. I race that,
stock cars...

22:43.095 --> 22:45.257
See, I got this dream
of being the first black driver

22:45.364 --> 22:47.526
in the Indy 500.

22:47.633 --> 22:50.466
I'll tell you something, man,
that would be a milestone.

22:50.569 --> 22:52.162
- You tell it.
- I hope you make it.

22:52.271 --> 22:53.602
- I will. I promise you.
- All right.

22:53.706 --> 22:56.266
Hold up.
How'd you find such a rare bike?

22:56.375 --> 22:57.934
How'd you get your hands
on that?

22:58.043 --> 22:58.942
I stole it.

22:59.044 --> 23:00.705
Whoa!

23:00.813 --> 23:03.111
- I'm kidding.
- I knew that. I knew that.

23:10.222 --> 23:12.247
What happened
to Richie's parrot?

23:12.358 --> 23:15.191
Oh, brother. What a jerk.

23:15.294 --> 23:18.059
And the goat?
(laughs)

23:18.163 --> 23:19.290
Yeah.

23:19.398 --> 23:20.524
I'll see you tomorrow, Jenny.

23:20.633 --> 23:21.759
Thanks a lot.

23:21.867 --> 23:22.925
Oh, brother.

23:23.035 --> 23:23.934
(chuckles)

23:24.036 --> 23:25.094
What happened, dear?

23:25.204 --> 23:27.798
Well, the caballeros
were onstage singing,

23:27.907 --> 23:29.306
and, uh...

23:29.408 --> 23:31.399
Hey, Rich.

23:32.945 --> 23:35.107
This parrot has seen
its last cracker.

23:35.214 --> 23:36.147
Tell Mom about it.

23:36.248 --> 23:37.943
It's really funny.
(laughs)

23:39.685 --> 23:41.778
How was I supposed to know
that Pi Nu

23:41.887 --> 23:44.220
had a live falcon
for a mascot?

23:47.893 --> 23:50.624
Oh, that's terrible.

23:50.729 --> 23:53.756
Well-well, how did you do
in the contest?

23:55.501 --> 23:58.402
Only one group came in below us.

23:58.504 --> 24:01.064
- MARION: Aw...
- Kappa Kappa Kappa.

24:01.173 --> 24:03.506
They didn't show up.

24:05.577 --> 24:07.409
But Jenny already told me
about that.

24:07.513 --> 24:10.141
But did they get Ralph
out of the bass drum?

24:11.917 --> 24:14.477
- Hi, sweetheart.
- Oh, Howard.

24:14.586 --> 24:16.077
How did Richie do
in the contest?

24:16.188 --> 24:18.953
He... was runner-up.

24:19.058 --> 24:20.616
I don't know how.

24:20.726 --> 24:23.286
Listen, I've been going over
the books down at the store,

24:23.395 --> 24:25.694
and I can't for the life of me
figure out

24:25.798 --> 24:28.631
how you turned a penny sale
into a profit.

24:28.734 --> 24:29.894
Howard, it's simple.

24:30.002 --> 24:32.368
It's like baked potatoes.

24:35.341 --> 24:37.206
Baked potatoes?

24:37.309 --> 24:38.709
Yes. When you eat
baked potatoes,

24:38.811 --> 24:40.904
you're gonna need salt
and pepper and butter,

24:41.013 --> 24:44.176
sour cream, chives...
and when you paint,

24:44.283 --> 24:46.183
you're gonna need
turpentine, drop cloths,

24:46.285 --> 24:48.344
brushes, buckets, rollers...

24:48.454 --> 24:52.891
You make your money
on the chives and sour cream.

